    PB_Festival_Title: "Pchum Ben Festival",
    PB_Detail:
      "Pchum Ben Festival is a significant Buddhist festival in Cambodia and one of the major royal ceremonies celebrated throughout the country. It takes place over 15 days, starting from the 1st day of the waning moon until the 15th day of the waning moon in the month of Pheaktob (September/October).Celebration of Pchum Ben Festival:Making Offerings (Ben):The festival involves making offerings to deceased ancestors, including parents, siblings, and relatives, whose rebirth is unknown. It is a time to honor and remember the departed. Historical Significance:In ancient times, the festival was organized to provide sustenance for monks who remained in the pagodas during the three-month rainy season retreat (Vassa). From the beginning of Vassa until its end, Buddhists would prepare offerings to ensure monks were well-supplied during this period. Challenges During the Rainy Season: Historical records note that during the rainy season, heavy rains made it difficult for monks to travel for alms rounds. Therefore, Buddhists would gather to ensure daily provisions for the monks until the end of Vassa. Merit-Making: The festival is also a time to dedicate merit to the spirits of deceased relatives through the power of offerings made to the monks. This act helps the spirits, who are believed to be suffering in the form of hungry ghosts (Preta), to find relief from their suffering.",
    Khmer_NewY_Title: "Khmer New Year",
    Khmer_NewY_Detail:
      "The Khmer New Year tradition involves a three-day celebration. The first day is called Maha Songkran, the second day is Wanabat, and the third day is Leung Sakk. The specific month, day, hour, and minute when the old year ends and the new year begins are precisely determined by ancient horoscopic calculations, known as the Maha Songkran. From the Angkor period onwards, Khmer people used the lunar calendar, starting the new year in the month of Mekasay (first month) and ending in the month of Kattik (twelfth month). Later, the solar calendar became more prevalent, with the new year beginning in the month of Chait (fifth month), typically around April 13th each year. Occasionally, the new year starts on April 14th. The solar calendar method is referred to as Samnanh Sankranta (when the sun passes directly overhead) and the lunar calendar method as Ayun Sankranta (when the suns path is oblique). Three-day Celebration: Maha Songkran: Marks the end of the old year and the beginning of the new year. This transition is calculated based on traditional horoscopic methods. Wanabat: The second day, dedicated to charitable activities, offering help to the poor, servants, and needy people. Leung Sakk:The third day, symbolizing the beginning of the new year’s official calendar. It involves various religious and cultural ceremonies.",
